Housing Price Prediction

Ryan Sosinski, Naveen Kumar Reddy Bandagunda, Anand Surendran Nair, Damon Nicholas

2/25/2022

Introduction:

With the housing market’s rapid appreciation in value the last few years, our group found this topic to be an interesting subject. With startups such as Opendoor creating an I-buy market, and other companies such as Redfin and Zillow chasing after them in terms of I-buy, data in the housing market is ever expanding. I-buy is the ability to sell a property on one of these businesses phone applications within seconds without the need of a realtor. To make this a reality, data analysis is needed to take several attributes and determine a fair market value offer, as a low offer will get ignored and an offer too high will hurt the business bad in profitability margins. Last year, it was also shown how little room for error data analysis is in the I-buy when Zillow temporarily exited the market due to their algorithm being unsuccessful and them losing a lot of money in that market. As a result, we think the ability to use attributes to determine housing prices is going to be an ever expanding skill needed in the real world today. When coming across the Dataset in Kaggle, we quickly determined this would be a good dataset to work with.

This dataset is related to housing prices, and lists other attributes such as area, bedrooms, ect. There are 13 attributes total in this dataset. In total, the following attributes in this dataset are: Price, area, bedrooms, bathrooms, stories, mainroad, guestroom, basement, hotwaterheating, airconditioning, parking, prefarea, and furningstatus. Price is the housing price, and it is a numeric value. Area is the area of the property and it is a numeric value. Bedrooms is how many bedrooms are included in the property and it is a numeric value. Bathrooms is how many bathrooms are included in the property and it is a numeric value. Stories is how many levels are included in the property and it is a numeric value. Mainroad is whether the property is on a mainroad and that is a yes/no value. Guestroom is whether or not the property includes a guestroom and that is a yes/no value. Basement is whether or not the property includes a basement and that is a yes/no value. Hotwaterheating is whether the property currently has hot water and that is a yes/no value. Airconditioning is whether or not the property contains airconditioning and that is a yes/no value. Parking is how many parking spaces the property has and it is a numeric value. Prefarea is whether the property is in a preferred area and it is a yes/no value. Furnishingstatus is whether the property is furnished and it is a value of furnished/semi-furnished/unfurnished.

Data source:

https://www.kaggle.com/yasserh/housing-prices-dataset

####Takeaways For our exploratory data analysis we used GGplot to use a various number of visualizations to see if certain variables had a relationship with price.

GGplot

-Histogram of Prices with density plot. As we can see with this histogram, prices are not normally distributed. Prices skew to the lower costs, and the outliers ten to be the ultra-expensive houses.

-Histogram of area with density plot. This histogram also skews to the left. Bigger area properties are outliers in this visualization.

-Scatter plot price vs area, with regression line. There appears to be a linear relationship between area and price. The linear regression of this dataset will be addressed in the linear regression portion as well.

-Box plot of price in regards to location on main road. Properties on a main road have a higher mean and a higher variance than houses not on a main road. If we were to interpret the variance, the prediction would be that non main road houses tend to be suburban projects of similarly priced properties.

-Box plot of price by whether or not it has a guest room. Unsurprisingly, properties with guestrooms tend to have more value. Although in regards to outliers, the most expensive properties do not have a guest room.

-Box plot of price by whether or not it has basement. Properties with basements have a higher mean value. Similar to the guestrooms though, the outliers of no basement are the highest property values in the dataset.

-Box plot of price by whether or not it has hot water heating. The mean of properties with hot water heating are higher. The most valuable properties (outliers) do not have hot water heating.

-Box plot of price by whether or not it has air conditioning. Air-conditioned properties have a higher mean value.

-Box plot of price by furnishing status. Unfurnished properties have the lowest mean in price. Semi furnished have the middle mean in price. Furnished properties have the highest mean in price. This is as expected.

-Box plot of price by whether or not the property is in a preferred area. Preferred area properties have a higher mean price, unsurprisingly.

Looking at the MSE values and the Adjusted R-squared of all the models, full model seems to be working fine with the data.

Lets try building the model using Regression trees

4.Regression tree

fit.tree<-rpart(formula=price~., data = train_Housing)
plotcp(fit.tree)
printcp(fit.tree)

Plot of the tree:

prp(fit.tree)

test_pred <- predict(fit.tree, test_Housing)
MSE.tree<-mean((test_Housing$price-test_pred)^2)

Plot of the tree after its pruned:

fit.tree.pruned<-prune(fit.tree, cp=0.022852)
prp(fit.tree.pruned)

test_pred1 <- predict(fit.tree.pruned, test_Housing)
MSE.tree_pruned<-mean((test_Housing$price-test_pred1)^2)

Tree before pruning performed better than the tree after pruning however, the MSE of the model is not better than the basic full linear regression model.

data.frame(MSE_full_model, MSE_AIC_model, MSE_BIC_model, MSE.tree, MSE.tree_pruned)
##   MSE_full_model MSE_AIC_model MSE_BIC_model     MSE.tree MSE.tree_pruned
## 1   1.088629e+12   1.07407e+12  1.044249e+12 1.354155e+12    1.513601e+12

We can see AIC selection model seems to be better than all the other models. So we suggest that model to be used for prediction of Housing prices.

New Functions

Broom Package

Broom is an output cleaning function developed to try and resolve the issue of tidy inputs not generating tidy outputs in R, which makes it more difficult on the user to efficiently compare and combine results from multiple models. This was helpful in our situation because we were comparing the outputs of two similar models, as considering the package’s effect on the “Quality of Life” for using R as a statistical tool. Looking at the below outputs, each tibble quickly summarizes the AIC and BIC models and allows for quicker and easier comparison when distinguishing it from the standard model’s output. The glance function was used for this example, but in our research, Broom users also commonly use the tidy and augment functions to improve standard R outputs.

glance(aic.model)

Data Explorer package

While searching around for new R packages to explorer, one that we noticed a lot of appreciation for was Data Explorer. It is a Powerful package that runs a report for many aspects of data exploration that could be missed. Included in this report are counts of rows, columns, missing observersation (in case the data isn’t cleaned). There are histograms, bar charts, QQ plots, correlation analysis between attributes, principal and component analysis for variance. Overall, this package is one that we plan to use in the future. It gave us analysis of several aspects that we may have missed in our freestyle exploratory analysis.
